flowRoot.flowPara: The pulse programmer is a collection of electronic devices assembled into a device called the "yellow box." Pulse programs are written on a computer, then transmitted to a Field Programmable Gate Array (FPGA), which then executes the program. The output signals can be sent to Direct Digital Synthesis (DDS) or Digital to Analog Converter (DAC) boards to shape them into arbitrary waveforms. Physicists are currently using the pulse programmer to control lasers in trapped-ion experiments, which may lead to the development of a quantum computer.

To make it easier for physicists to assemble their yellow boxes, David is developing a new clock source board. It contains our current VCO chip, with a divider chip that also serves as a "fanout," meaning that it provides multiple 800 MHz and 100 MHz outputs for multiple devices to connect to.
Jeff Booth, Rob McClure, David Nufer
Paul Pham, Carl Ebeling Ph.D
Computer Science and Engineering, University of Washington

Input counting allows the pulse sequencer board to act on inputs from photon counters. This new feature has been requested by the physicists that use the pulse programmer. It allows them to create programs that behave dynamically, based on the input signals. For example, they can hook up a PMT into one of the inputs, and use the counts to determine whether it is light or dark in the room. The program can then behave differently, based on that observation.
For input counting to work, both the firmware and the pulse program compiler had to be modified.

The clock source keeps the components of the yellow box synchronized. It generates a 100 MHz square wave for the sequencer board and a 800 MHz square wave for the DDS boards that create the custom waveforms.
The clock source is comprised of two components: the voltage-controlled oscillator (VCO) and the clock divider.

The VCO generates a 1600 MHz clock signal from an onboard clock crystal. The clock divider converts this into 800 MHz and 100 MHz clock signals. The VCO (and sometimes the divider, depending on the model) must be programmed when it is powered on. Jeff built a Python script to program the oscillator using the sequencer board, replacing the proprietary Windows program that used to do this task.

When we started this project, the firmware for the FPGA was several years old, and would not compile on Altera Quartus 9. Once Rob made it compile, it refused to work! Rob used SignalTap software to monitor signals on the board as it ran, and discovered that the arbiters on the board had delay values that were too low. Thanks to Rob's work, the firmware is functional on the latest compiler.

The sequencer board communicates with computers via an Ethernet interface, so it needs an IP address. Originally, the IP address was determined based on the settings of the board's DIP switches. The board is capable of requesting an IP address via DHCP, but it only gets this address for a limited time. Jeff is working on a lease timer to determine when the board should renew its address.
